T1  - Financial Innovation and Financial Intermediation: Evidence from Credit Default Swaps
AU  - Butler, Alexander W.
AU  - Gao, Xiang
AU  - Uzmanoglu, Cihan
Y1  - 2020/07/21
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3560
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3560
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3150
EP  - 3173
VL  - 67
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We study the influence of credit default swaps (CDS) trading on the costs of bond intermediation. After CDS initiation, CDS firms pay 12% to 28% (8 to 20 basis points) lower underwriting fees than similar non-CDS firms do. Underwriting fees decline more for riskier issuers and illiquid bonds for which the ability to hedge with CDS is more valuable. In bond offerings, participation by investors facing risk-based regulatory requirements increases after CDS initiation. Our evidence suggests that CDS-driven innovations in risk sharing contribute to the transactional efficiency of the market by reducing the financial intermediation costs of placing bonds.This paper was accepted by Karl Diether, finance.
AB  - We study the influence of credit default swaps (CDS) trading on the costs of bond intermediation. After CDS initiation, CDS firms pay 12% to 28% (8 to 20 basis points) lower underwriting fees than similar non-CDS firms do. Underwriting fees decline more for riskier issuers and illiquid bonds for which the ability to hedge with CDS is more valuable. In bond offerings, participation by investors facing risk-based regulatory requirements increases after CDS initiation. Our evidence suggests that CDS-driven innovations in risk sharing contribute to the transactional efficiency of the market by reducing the financial intermediation costs of placing bonds.This paper was accepted by Karl Diether, finance.
